'''Human endogenous retrovirus K''' ('''HERV-K''') or '''Human teratocarcinoma-derived virus''' ('''HDTV''') is a family of [[human endogenous retrovirus]]es associated with malignant tumors of the testes.<ref>{{Cite book|author=Boeke JD, Stoye JP|title=Retrotransposons, endogenous retroviruses, and the evolution of retroelements|work=Retroviruses|editor1=JM Coffin|editor2=SH Hughes |editor3=HE Varmus |location=Cold Spring Harbor, New York |publisher=Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory Press |date=1997|pages=343–435}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Boller|first1=Klaus|last2=König|first2=Herbert|last3=Sauter|first3=Marlies|last4=Mueller-Lantzsch|first4=Nikolaus|last5=Löwer|first5=Roswitha|last6=Löwer|first6=Johannes|last7=Kurth|first7=Reinhard|title=Evidence That HERV-K Is the Endogenous Retrovirus Sequence That Codes for the Human Teratocarcinoma-Derived Retrovirus HTDV|journal=Virology|date=September 1993|volume=196|issue=1|pages=349–353|doi=10.1006/viro.1993.1487 |pmid=8356806}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Löwer|first1=J|last2=Wondrak|first2=EM|last3=Kurth|first3=R|title=Genome analysis and reverse transcriptase activity of human teratocarcinoma-derived retroviruses.|journal=The Journal of General Virology|date=November 1987|volume=68|pages=2807–15|pmid=2445905|issue=11|doi=10.1099/0022-1317-68-11-2807}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Rédei|first1=George P.|title=Encyclopedia of genetics, genomics, proteomics, and informatics|date=2008|publisher=Springer| isbn=978-1-4020-6754-9|edition=3rd}}</ref> HERV-K is also found in apes and [[Old World monkeys]].

In 1999 Barbulescu, ''et al.'' showed that, of ten HERV-K [[provirus]]es cloned, eight were unique to humans, while one was shared with [[chimpanzee]]s and [[bonobo]]s, and one with chimpanzees, bonobos and [[gorilla]]s.<ref>{{Cite journal |author1=Madalina Barbulescu |author2=Geoffrey Turner |author3=Michael I. Seaman† |author4=Amos S. Deinard‡§ |author5=Kenneth K. Kidd |author6=Jack Lenz |title=Many human endogenous retrovirus K (HERV-K) proviruses are unique to humans |work=Current Biology |date=1999 |volume=9 |doi=10.1016/s0960-9822(99)80390-x |pages=861–8 |url=http://tools.medicine.yale.edu/kidd/www/377.pdf |pmid=10469592 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130228083443/http://tools.medicine.yale.edu/kidd/www/377.pdf |archivedate=28 February 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>

In 2015 Grow ''et al.'' demonstrated that HERV-K is transcribed during embryogenesis from the eight cell stage up to the stem cell derivation.<ref name="Grow">{{Cite journal |title=Intrinsic retroviral reactivation in human preimplantation embryos and pluripotent cells |author1=Edward J. Grow |author2=Ryan A. Flynn |author3=Shawn L. Chavez |author4=Nicholas L. Bayless |author5=Mark Wossidlo |author6=Daniel J. Wesche |author7=Lance Martin |author8=Carol B. Ware |author9=Catherine A. Blish |author10=Howard Y. Chang|authorlink10=Howard Y. Chang |author11=Renee A. Reijo Pera |author12=Joanna Wysocka |journal=Nature |volume=522 |pages=221–5 |date=11 June 2015 |doi=10.1038/nature14308 |pmid=25896322 |pmc=4503379}}</ref>  Furthermore, overexpression of the HERV-K accessory protein [[Rec (protein)|Rec]] increases IFITM1 levels on the cell surface and inhibits viral infection.<ref name="Grow" /><ref name="HML-2">{{cite journal|vauthors=Hanke K, Hohn O, Bannert N |title=HERV-K(HML-2), a seemingly silent subtenant – but still waters run deep |journal=[[APMIS]] |date=January–February 2016 |volume=124 |issue=1–2 |pages=67–87 |pmid=26818263 |doi=10.1111/apm.12475}}</ref>

